15A   Quiz

You are familiar with the compartments of the thigh from Unit 3. Each compartment of the thigh is associated with a dominant movement: muscles of the anterior compartment of the thigh (the quadriceps) predominantly extend the knee, while muscles of the posterior compartment of the thigh (the hamstrings) predominantly flex the knee. The muscles of the medial compartment (the adductors) of the thigh predominantly adduct the hip.
Fortunately for us, trying to learn the relationships between peripheral nerves and movements, each compartment contains a different peripheral nerve, and therefore each movement is also associated with a different peripheral nerve.

From the lumbar plexus,  the femoral nerve innervates the muscles of the anterior (extensor) compartment of the thigh, and the obturator nerve innervates most of the muscles in the medial (adductor) compartment of the thigh. 
From the sacral plexus, the sciatic nerve innervates the muscles of the posterior (flexor) compartment of the thigh.
